comments.text:
It's true that 12GB would be the ideal choice — and most people agree on that. However, even 10GB would be sufficient in many cases, as games at 1080p or 1440p often only slightly exceed 8–8.5GB of VRAM usage. Additionally, the operating system and background applications consume VRAM as well. Tools such as MSI Afterburner, Discord, Steam, iCUE, and other overlays contribute to this. For instance, MSI Afterburner alone can take up around 100MB. That's what we call allocated memory or vram. 

I have an RTX 4070 Ti Super with 16GB, of course, and I often see games that barely go over 8GB. A card like the 3080 will handle things better — not just because of its faster chip (even though it’s two generations older), but mainly because those 10GB of VRAM really make a difference.

In my case, Windows 11 and other applications (Steam, Discord, iCUE, Chrome with YouTube) use up around 1500MB of VRAM on their own.

comments.text:
The bus is 448GB/s, there is no issue with bandwidth. The only issue is people buying literally the cheapest card a manufacturer makes and then expecting it to run things at high resolution and ultra settings at 100FPS in console ports.

If you play the games most people play - online multiplayer games with much lower GPU demand - this will be a great card. For "modern titles" (bad console single player ports) turn down textures a notch, do not turn on raytracing. Done. Games all look great, no issue with 8GB VRAM.

It's crazy to see people who can barely scrape together $300 for a GPU and who are running GPUs from 5+ years ago complain that a card better than the one they have doesn't have enough VRAM. The same person running at medium settings with mediocre framerates is complaining about a card that gets better framerates at high settings and is literally the cheapest one from this generation on the market.
